drug.name: Dicyclomine
drug.description:
Dicyclomine is a muscarinic M1 and M2 receptor antagonist as well as a non-competitive inhibitor of histamine and bradykinin used to treat spasms of the intestines seen in functional bowel disorder and irritable bowel syndrome.[A6556,A182555,L7967] Though it is commonly prescribed, its recommendation may have been based on a small amount of evidence and so its prescription is becoming less favourable.[L7982]
Dicyclomine was granted FDA approval on 11 May 1950.[L7967]

drug.indication: Dicyclomine is indicated for the treatment of functional bowel disorder and irritable bowel syndrome.[L7967]
drug.pharmacodynamics: Dicyclomine is an anticholinergic drug used to relax the smooth muscles of the intestines.[L7967] It's duration of action is not especially long as it is usually taken 4 times daily with individual doses of 20-40mg orally or 10-20mg by intramuscular injection.[L7967] Dicyclomine should not be administered intravenously.[L7967]
drug.mechanism-of-action: Dicyclomine achieves its action partially through direct antimuscarinic activity of the M1 and M2 receptors, and partially through antagonism of bradykinin and histamine.[A6556,A182555,L7967] Dicyclomine non-competitively inhibits the action of bradykinin and histamine, resulting in direct action on the smooth muscle, and decreased strength of contractions seen in spasms of the ileum.[A182555]
drug.toxicity:
Patients experiencing an overdose may present with headache, nausea, vomiting, blurred vision, dilated pupils, dizziness, dry mouth, difficulty swallowing, CNS stimulation, as well as hot, dry skin.[L7967] Treat patients with gastric lavage, emetics, activated charcoal, sedatives for excitement, and a cholinergic agent if indicated.[L7967]
The oral LD<sub>50</sub> in mice is 625mg/kg.[L7967]
drug.metabolism: The metabolism of dicyclomine has not been well researched.[A182525]
drug.absorption: The bioavailability of dicyclomine has not been determined,[A182534] though it is likely well absorbed as the primary route of elimination is in the urine.[A182525,L7967] Dicyclomine has a T<sub>max</sub> of 1-1.5h.[L7967]
drug.half-life: The mean plasma elimination half life is approximately 1.8 hours.[A182525,L7967]
drug.protein-binding: Data regarding plasma protein binding of dicyclomine is not readily available.[L7967]
drug.route-of-elimination: Dicyclomine is 79.5% eliminated in the urine and 8.4% in the feces.[A182525,L7967]
drug.volume-of-distribution: The volume of distribution for a 20mg oral dose is 3.65L/kg.[L7967]
drug.clearance: Data regarding the clearance of dicyclomine is not readily available.[L7967]

polypeptide.name: Muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M1
polypeptide.specific-function: The muscarinic acetylcholine receptor mediates various cellular responses, including inhibition of adenylate cyclase, breakdown of phosphoinositides and modulation of potassium channels through the action of G proteins. Primary transducing effect is Pi turnover.

polypeptide.name: Muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M2
polypeptide.specific-function: The muscarinic acetylcholine receptor mediates various cellular responses, including inhibition of adenylate cyclase, breakdown of phosphoinositides and modulation of potassium channels through the action of G proteins. Primary transducing effect is adenylate cyclase inhibition. Signaling promotes phospholipase C activity, leading to the release of inositol trisphosphate (IP3); this then triggers calcium ion release into the cytosol.
